{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/data-transformation-e39bd132b66", "time": 1683009580.596004, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/data-transformation-e39bd132b66/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Data Transformation. Understanding why the \u201cUnsexy\u201d\u2026 | by Goutham Dommaraju | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Data Transformation", "description": "Understand how data transformation helps machine learning pipelines perform better. Gain insight into how to transform non-linear problems into linear ones."}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://gist.github.com/GouthamDommaraju/08afd71485ef7bc94273f912fa1ccd44", "anchor_text": "this", "paragraph_index": 17}], "all_paragraphs": ["When we talk about data science, we are biased to start with sexy aspects like Artificial Intelligence (AI), Machine Learning (ML), predicting the future, and so on. Like our brain, which tries to simulate the future from past experiences, ML algorithms work and learn from the past, and it\u2019s our job to provide them with the best possible learning experiences.", "Did you ever wonder how you could close your eyes right now and experience the rush of that speech you are going to deliver to a broad audience tomorrow?", "In the first half of this article, we will look at simple use cases that will help us understand why data transformation is essential and how it can help our classifiers perform better. In the latter half, we will visually understand why performing a log-transformation on the exponential feature will allow us to use linear regression to model it.", "We are trying to classify cars into two types-red and green based on feature x, and we plotted the values of x for the different car IDs below.", "As you can see, our classifier will have to draw a parallelogram boundary around the red region to identify the different cars accurately.", "Now, think what would happen if we used the feature absolute(x) or |x| instead of x?", "As shown above, the classifier can draw a straight line and classify the data accurately.", "How cool is that! We converted a non-linear classification problem into a linear one by performing a simple data transformation on the feature x. This transformation would allow us to use linear classifiers, or if we still want to use sophisticated non-linear classifiers, reduce their workload. Analogy \u2014 Imagine that you are in your kindergarten art class, and your teacher asked you to draw either a straight line or a parallelogram. What would you pick? Why?", "Another operation on the feature x that would transform the problem into a linear classification would be square(x).", "Say, we have two features f1 and f2 for the different cars, and we plotted them below. Can you think of a transformation on (f1,f2) that would convert this into a linear classification problem?", "Say our boss wants us to predict the value of y for a specific x. Being a responsible data scientist, we visualized y for the different values of our feature x, and the plot is as shown below.", "After looking at the above plot, we know that the relationship between x and y is not linear. We might consider using an exponential model, which makes perfect sense, given the shape of the scatter plot. But, before that, let\u2019s consider plotting x and log(y).", "Once we transformed y to log(y), we could use a straight line to model x and log(y). This operation is known as logarithmic transformation and is used on exponential data to make it linear. Note that x and y are still non linearly related. But, because of transformation, we could fit a linear regression line, and it\u2019s not tricky to mathematically unwind from our linear model back to an exponential one.", "Additionally, linear regression is the champion for explainability and the ability to provide actionable insights by quantifying the effect of different predictors on the dependent variable and is cherished by many business stakeholders.", "There is no universal way of transforming data. Understanding what your model likes and providing it with inputs in that format would drastically improve the performance of your ML pipeline.", "Please note that at times, data transformation might:", "After reading this article, I hope that you are biased to start with data exploration. Before you jump into training a sophisticated model, try to understand if any transformation would benefit your machine learning model.", "I created all the visualizations in this article using Matplotlib, and the code is present in this GitHub Gist.", "I want to end by thanking my friend Sam for proofreading this article.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fe39bd132b66&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fdata-transformation-e39bd132b66&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fdata-transformation-e39bd132b66&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redir